A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
MISSION DESCRIPTION
Formally designated mission-critical, RAND Project Air Force (PAF) is the Department of the Air Force's (DAF's) sole Congressionally Mandated Federally Funded
Research and Development Center (FFRDC) for studies and analysis. For 78 years, PAF has provided essential, objective analysis to inform DAF and Congressional
decisions, with a research agenda directed by the DAF's highest levels, including the Tri-Chair Steering Group chaired by the USecAF, VCSAF, and VCSO.

 PAF provides a return on investment that far exceeds its costs. Its actionable recommendations have saved billions of dollars while maximizing lethality and readiness.
 Recent examples include saving $17 billion from an airlift recapitalization strategy and preventing a $30 billion budgetary spike through analysis of the Future Aerial
 Refueling Enterprise.

 PAF research informs the DAF's most crucial decisions, from Collaborative Combat Aircraft (CCA) force design and cost-effective air base resilience to improving
 space acquisition. Notably, PAF's latest work on Dynamic Space Operations (DSO) directly influenced the VCSO's strategy for refueling spacecraft and is being used to
 formally respond to a FY 2026 Congressional requirement.

 This program is in Budget Activity 6, RDT&E Management Support because this budget activity includes research, development, test and evaluation efforts and funds to
 sustain and/or modernize the installations or operations required for general research, development, test and evaluation.

