D. Acquisition Strategy
The first MRC battery was delivered in FY 2023, consisting of one BOC with support vehicles, four launchers, and a reload capability. The initial delivery also included
the first eight Tomahawk and eight Standard Missile-6 (SM-6) missiles for operational use. Development, delivery, and fielding of the remaining three MRC batteries is
ongoing.

 Battery 2 was delivered in 4Q2024, Battery 3 was delivered in 4Q2025, and Battery 4's anticipated delivery date from contractor is 4Q2026 under the Middle Tier of
 Acquisition Rapid Prototyping (MTA RP) Acquisition pathway. MRC is currently pursuing an extension to the existing MTA RP with an updated Acquisition Decision
 Memorandum.

 For Batteries 2 through 4, MRC will use mature technologies and software and continue to evolve them though technology insertion to meet operational needs within the
 Army's required delivery timeline. The MTA RP strategy reduces program risk, allows for technology upgrades with each battery and enables industry to quickly deliver
 capability within the five-year window. The Navy's Vertical Launching System, Tomahawk, and SM-6 are all fielded systems with an extensive track record of operational
 success. The MRC program integrates the missiles, launchers, and command and control hardware into a land-based configuration with the goal of staying common
 with the Navy's fielded systems. This approach minimizes developmental efforts and thereby reduces overall technical risk. Known technology improvements, such as
 wireless and beyond line-of-sight communications, survivability upgrades, command and control virtualization, and incorporation of future missile variants, necessitate
 changes to each battery.

 The existing Other Transaction Authority (OTA) agreement, which was novated to Army Contracting Command-Redstone Arsenal (ACC-RSA) in January 2024, was
 utilized to support program execution. The OTA included exercised Cost-Plus-Fixed-Fee options for Batteries 2 through 4. The program utilized existing contract vehicles
 to procure items already in production, including Army contracts for standard trucks, trailers, and generators, and Navy contracts supporting Tomahawk and SM-6.

 ACC-RSA awarded a Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) based contract in April 2025 to enable continued weapon system modifications (WSMs) to include
 development engineering and design efforts for a RBF. ACC RSA awarded a FAR based contract in 1Q FY 2026 for integrated logistics support to ensure operational
 effectiveness of fielded batteries.

 Based on available data rights and industry partner capabilities, the program office identified WSMs appropriate for execution by vendors other than the OEM. These
 WSMs were separated from the core scope, and the resulting modification kits will be delivered as Government-Furnished Equipment (GFE) to the OEM for final
 integration.




