Appropriation/Budget Activity                                                       R-1 Program Element (Number/Name)
3600: Research, Development, Test & Evaluation, Air Force / BA 7:                   PE 0101126F / B-1B Squadrons
Operational Systems Development
 Air Force Global Strike Command requirement document 1067 23-075, signed Q3 FY 2024, amended Q4 FY 2025 identified a need for a critical upgrade to Bombers
 beyond-line-of-sight (BLOS) communication capabilities. The current legacy data network is outdated and unreliable, leading to connectivity issues that hinder effective
 command and control (C2) and isolate combat air forces from the Air Operations Center (AOC) and the Combatant Commander. This degradation of situational
 awareness and communication negatively impacts mission execution and the ability to process information at the tactical edge. To address this capability gap, a modern,
 resilient, and reliable BLOS networking capability is required. This will support the transition to a Joint Fires Network (JFN) and the broader Joint All-Domain Command
 and Control (JADC2) concept.
 The solution will provide robust cyber defense, optimize aircraft weapons and routing, and enable the transfer of J-series messages and digital files via Transmission
 Control Protocol / Internet Protocol (TCP/IP) interfaces. The system must be fully integrated with existing aircraft power, cooling, and data bus systems, while also
 considering open architecture for future technological advancements.

HYBRID Satellite Communications (SATCOM) provides resilient communication using Proliferated Low Earth Orbit (pLEO) satellites, providing the B-1B communication
in contested environments. Securing alternate network connectivity and pathways will ensure long-range re-targeting capability and increase combat effectiveness
through a modern, resilient, and reliable construct. Without this capability, there is a risk of isolating combat air forces from the Air Operations Center and the Combatant
Commander.

Urgent operational requirement identified Q2 FY 2026 to field initial capability utilizing Tactical Airborne Communication Kit (TACKit) within one year. TACKit will provide
network connectivity for Beyond Line of Sight (BLOS) secure data until the Hybrid SATCOM solution is fully fielded in 2030.

EXTERNAL HEAVY-STORES PYLON:
Air Force Global Strike Command requirement document 1067 23-85, signed Q2 FY 2024 identified a need to Maximize carriage of existing standoff munitions on the
B-1B. The B-1B is the premiere standoff weapon employment platform, carrying more AGM-158B/C Joint Air-to-Surface Standoff Missile (JASSM) and Long-Range Anti-
Ship Missile (LRASM) than any other Combat Air Force (CAF) Asset. The B-1B provides mass, maneuver, and economy of force to combatant commanders. AFGSC,
as the force provider of long-range strike and lead-Major Command (MAJCOM) for standoff attack weapons, provided guidance to pursue external carry on the B-1B.
During the stand-up of the future bomber force (B-21 emergence and B-52 upgrades), the B-1B will be the primary bomber available to combatant commanders.

External Heavy-Stores Pylon program builds on the accomplishments of the Hypersonic Integration Program, a Congressional Add, by providing increased carriage
capacity of external stores on the B-1B aircraft. Maximum carriage of external weapons on the B-1B provides near-term increased volume of fires and serves to mitigate
transition risk of the Air Force bomber fleet prior to the emergence of the B-21 as a combat bomber.

HYPERSONIC INTEGRATION:
The FY 2022 and FY 2023 Conference Appropriations, detailed in the Congressional Conference Reports of Interest, added 20.0 million (10.0 million in FY 2022 and
10.0 million in FY 2023) Research Testing Development and Evaluation (RTD&E) appropriation for B-1B hypersonic weapon integration. This funding developed an
external carry-enabled testbed facilitating rapid integration of priority hypersonic weapons in support of national security objectives, leading to potential investment
opportunities for weapon programs. This program provides an opportunity to significantly reduce risk for an operational external carry capability on the B-1B if directed.



