C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                 FY 2025     FY 2026       FY 2027
Title: Physics-based Machine Learning Methodologies for Generative Design                                                                  -        0.000         4.017
Description: This initiative advances next-generation aerial vehicle design and autonomy by integrating physics-based machine
learning (PBML) with generative and foundation model (FM) approaches. Traditional generative design excels in commodity
applications but fails to capture the complex aerodynamic, structural, and signature requirements of aerospace systems. By
embedding governing physics into ML models, we will deliver accelerated, lower-dimensional tools that preserve fidelity while
reducing computational burden—enabling rapid, mission-relevant design exploration of attritable aerial vehicles.

Next, we will develop resilient autonomy for low-SWaP (Size, Weight, and Power) and attritable aerial vehicles. FMs promise
Level 5 autonomy in automotive applications as they enable commonsense decision-making by leveraging human knowledge
inferred from internet-scale data. However, safety is paramount. Our research will advance the application of FMs to the aerial
domain, developing frameworks that judiciously introduce FMs in the autonomy stack. This research will also incorporate
reachability theory and AI safety validation frameworks to ensure FM-enabled autonomy meets DoD operational standards.

Finally, we will address resource efficiency. PBML generative design and FM autonomy models are computationally intensive,
often requiring billions of parameters. We will pursue GPU optimization, model distillation, pruning, and hardware-software co-
design to achieve real-time execution under the size, weight, power, and cost constraints critical for DoD systems.

This program delivers transformative design and autonomy capabilities while aligning with priorities for efficiency, safety, and
operational readiness in future aerial systems.

FY 2026 Plans:
N/A.
FY 2027 Plans:
In FY27, we will lay the technical and organizational foundation for this program across three integrated thrusts: physics-based
generative design, FM-enabled autonomy, and efficient AI computing.

1. Physics-Based Generative Design (PBML-GD):

Develop model hierarchies to balance fidelity and efficiency in aerodynamic, structural, and signature simulations.

Launch efforts to embed governing physics directly into ML models to ensure design outputs are operationally relevant.

Management Support

C. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                   FY 2025      FY 2026      FY 2027
Begin construction of a generative design language model framework to translate mission-level requirements into candidate air
vehicle concepts.

2. Generative AI for Autonomy:

Initiate design of FM-backed autonomy stacks for low-SWaP (Size, Weight, and Power) and attritable vehicles, with an emphasis
on modular architectures.

Begin simulation-first training pipelines by creating photorealistic static 3D environments to support autonomy policy development.

Establish initial safety guardrails using neural reachability methods to provide design-time safety assurances.

3. Efficient AI Computing:

Optimize existing CFD and PBML solvers for GPU execution to accelerate design iteration and dataset generation.

Begin model distillation and pruning methods to reduce FM size for real-time performance on edge processors.

Start developing hardware-aware algorithmic optimizations to ensure scalability to future low-SWaP autonomous platforms.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY27 New Start.
